Experts in facility management have called for collaboration to improve health, safety in the operational environment, promote human activities and business continuity. Speaking at an event to mark World Facility Management Day in Lagos, with the theme, ‘Celebrating FM: Standing tall beyond the pandemic,’ they also called for synergy among players in the sector towards achieving an excellent built environment. The President, International Facility Management Association, Nigerian chapter, Mr Segun Adebayo, said the association would continue to create critical paths towards a better operating environment, adding that members were determined to achieve a sustainable and forward-thinking industry through capacity building, knowledge development and research. The keynote speaker and head of retail and consumer banking at Sterling Bank, Shina Atilola, said digitisation and COVID-19 fast-tracked the need for players in the built environment to capitalise on the emerging environment. Atilola explained that the pandemic provided an opportunity to change the narrative and urged facility managers to be proactive. In his remark, the Chairman, Nigerian Institute of Architects, Lagos chapter, David Majekodunmi, advised facility management practitioners to create a trust fund and invest more in research towards encouraging young Nigerians to be a part of the profession. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com